aina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cansfield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Cantsfield in Tunstall (Lancs), pronounced /ˈkansfi:ld/."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Cansfield was born in 1177, in Aldingham, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Cansfield, was 17 and his mother, Mrs. Cansfield, was 13. He had at least 2 sons with Ingrid de Austiorch. He died in 1250, in his hometown, at the age of 73."},"et":{"1177–1250":"1177–1250","1160–1220":"1160–1220","1190–1245":"1190–1245","1196–1225":"1196–1225","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1190":"1190","Abt 1196":"umbes 1196","1225":"1225","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1245":"1245","1177":"1177","1220":"1220","1165":"1165","1196":"1196","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","England":"England","Aldingham, Lancashir